<section xml:id="sec-Matlab_High_dimension_arrays" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>High Dimension  Arrays</title>

	<p>
		In this section, we look into some of the advanced arrays used in Matlab.
	</p>

	<p>
		So far, you have dealt with one dimensional arrays (vectors) and two dimensional arrays (matrices). It is also possible to represent higher dimension arrays in Matlab. A three dimensional array consists of a 'stack' of two dimensional arrays. Each two dimensional array is called a page. A three dimensional array can be created by first making a two dimensional array
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; A = [1,2,3; 4,5,6]
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	<p>
		Then a second page can be added by using a third argument when indexing <c>A</c>,
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; A(:,:,2) = [0,2,3; 1,4,0]
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	<p>
		This creates a 2x3x2 dimension array.
		You can add additional pages using this notation. The notation for indexing a three dimensional arrays is very similar to two dimensional arrays. For example,
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; x = A(1,3,2);
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	<p>
		defined x to be the element in the first row, third column, and second page.
