	<!--  Example use 1 -->

	<p>
		Suppose that you would like to store the temperature of a rectangular tray of brownies as they bake in an oven. The row and column of the matrix might represent the position in the pan, then the page represents the thickness of the brownies.
	</p>

	<p>
		Consider the
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,1) = [147,144,145,148; 143,140,142,145]
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,2) = [150,147,148,151; 146,142,145,147]
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,3) = [156,153,151,156; 149,145,147,150]
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	<p>
		A three dimensional array can be used to store the temperature as a a three dimensional array
	</p>

	<p>
		We might also want to use a fourth dimension to represent the temperature of the brownies at different times. The following would define the fourth dimension in out array <c>T</c>. This represents how the temperature of the brownies might change with respect to time.
	</p>

	<p>
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,:,2) = T+1;
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,:,3) = T(:,:,:,1)+2;
					&gt;&gt; T(:,:,:,4) = T(:,:,:,1)+3;
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>
	<p>
		If you want to see how the temperature of one point in the pan changes with respect to time, you would look at
		<sidebyside width="100%">
			<program language="matlab">
				<code>
					&gt;&gt; t = T(1,1,1,:);
				</code>
			</program>
		</sidebyside>
	</p>

